## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

### Inventory of issues

| Line | API | Problem in .NET 8 |
|------|-----|--------------------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `Thread.Abort` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown — cleanup code silently skipped |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `Thread.ResetAbort` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Pattern classification

This is a **cancellable work loop** + **ThreadAbortException as control flow** + **Thread.ResetAbort to continue execution**. All three must migrate to cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces the ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No need for ResetAbort — just let the loop condition exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forcible injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids swallowing unrelated exceptions |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | Not needed — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then Abort | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Waits for actual exit instead of sleeping a fixed time then killing |

### Critical pitfall: `GetNextItem` must cooperate

The biggest migration risk is that **`GetNextItem()` must accept and honor the token**. If it blocks on a `Queue`, `Socket`, or `WaitHandle` without checking the token, cancellation stalls. Examples:

```csharp
// If using BlockingCollection<T> (recommended):
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}

// If using a manual wait:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Replaces: _signal.WaitOne() which Thread.Abort used to interrupt
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If wrapping synchronous I/O that can't take a token:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        if (TryGetItemWithTimeout(out var item, millisecondsTimeout: 500))
            return item;
    }
    throw new OperationCanceledException(token);
}
```

### Additional pitfalls to watch for

1. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — it's `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The `IDisposable` pattern on the class handles this.

2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — the catch block here is appropriate because it's the top-level loop orchestrator. Don't catch it deeper in `ProcessItem` unless you have a specific recovery action.

3. **`Thread.Join` can hang forever** — if the thread is stuck in uncooperative blocking code and you can't pass a token, `Join(timeout)` will return `false`. At that point there is **no safe way** to force-kill it in .NET 8. The only escape hatch is moving uncooperative work to a child `Process` and using `Process.Kill()`.

4. **`Thread.Sleep` inside the loop** — if `ProcessLoop` or any callee uses `Thread.Sleep`, replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation wakes it immediately.
